<section xml:id="sect-four">

    <title>Categorical Data</title>

<objectives permid="Obj-4">
    <ul>
        <li>
            Introduce basic concepts and correct terminology for categorical data.
        </li>
    </ul>
</objectives>

<remark>
    <p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <term>Bar plot.</term><idx><h>Plot</h><h>bar</h></idx>
            It is the common plot to show a categorical variable.
        </li>

        <li>
            <term>Row proportions.</term><idx><h>Proportions</h><h>row</h></idx>
It is a way to show the quotient between one case compare to the total. This can be done horizontal.
        </li>        
        <li>
            <term>Column proportions.</term><idx><h>Proportions</h><h>column</h></idx>
It is a way to show the quotient between one case compare to the total. This should be done vertical.
        </li>                
<li>
    <term>bar plot with two variables</term><idx><h>Plot</h><h>bar with two variables</h></idx>
 is an extension for the bar plot. It is also called 
 <term>stacked bar plot.</term><idx><h>Plot</h><h>stacked bar</h></idx>
This kind of plot represents different groups of one varible stacked.
</li>

<li>
<term>Mosaic plots.</term><idx><h>Plot</h><h>Mosaic</h></idx>
This kind of plot uses areas to stand for the number of cases in each category.
</li>

<li>
    <term>Pie chart.</term><idx><h>Plot</h><h>Pie chart</h></idx>
    It is another to represent the information, similarly to 
    bar plot, but in a circle shape.
</li>
</ul>
    </p>
</remark>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            <me>
                \begin{array}{lccc} 
                            &amp; \text{text}&amp; \text{HTML}&amp; \text{Total}\\
            \text{Spam}     &amp; 364&amp;  764&amp; 1028\\
            \text{Not spam} &amp; 632&amp; 2345&amp; 2977\\
            \text{Total}    &amp; 996&amp; 3109&amp; 4005\\
                \end{array}
            </me>
            Calculate 
            <ol>
                <li>Row proportions</li>
                <li>Column proportions</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</example>


